    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi<br />I have to comment again so quickly as I have to admit I am somewhat confused. Reading through all the comments, (which admittedly I should have done before commenting the first time), I can see that roasting vegetables like carrots and broccoli seems to be the mainstay of cooking vegetables in the States. Is this correct? This is so alien to me as a normal way to cook veg. (I have tried roasted veg and do so occasionally, but it&#39;s not usual). It&#39;s the norm to boil everything in the UK or fry or braise in a skillet as your post shows, we even have a running joke that most UK cooks boil everything so much they turn to mush and most people hate veg because of terrible experiences of overcooked cauliflower etc. when children. It&#39;s interesting for me to get a real sense of how other cultures treat the things we all use often. (I am British living in Vancouver, BC)</p>
    </div>

